I had the same issue for a while, one thing I did was increase the airflow to the innards of the box itself.  Big Lots sales small desk top fans for less than $5.00.  Pull the side off of you machine and place da fan to blow in there and it will help cool the thing down.<br>
<br>
Castious was having the same issue, he tried this as well as blowing out all the dust and lint out of the box and I think he has become more stable.<br>
<br>
Just something that we have tried at the house running 3-4 boxes across the network playin EQ.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8o --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/nerd.gif ALT="8o"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>The not so silent monk from the House Valiant</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dashanvaliant>DashanValiant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 137<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/19/03 12:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1590.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Crashing Issues</span><hr size=1> Hurm.  I am finally beginning to believe the problem may be fixed, and I am not just having consistent luck.  NVidia, earlier this month, released a new set of drivers, to improve compatibility with Direct X 9.0 and probably XP as well.  It seems to have done the trick.  I hope.<br>
